songs.full_title: Signifying Rapper by Schoolly D
songs.title: Signifying Rapper

description.plain:
Schoolly’s classic reworking of the “Signifying Monkey” folklore. The “Signifying Monkey” is an African-American derivation (and mutation) of the (Nigerian) Yorùbá people’s trickster spirit Èṣù. In interactions with the Lion and the Elephant, the Monkey will most typically claim to “repeat” – while actually inventing – the Elephant’s harsh words about the Lion. Looking for vengeance, the Lion goes to see the Elephant and gets his ass soundly smacked down.

In Schoolly’s version of the tale, the “Signifying Rapper” is joined by the “Badass Pimp” and the “Big Bad Faggot”, filling the roles of the Lion and the Elephant, respectively. Interestingly, and uniquely for hip hop, the “faggot” of this song is one mean, tough motherfucker.

The beat samples Led Zep’s “Kashmir”. The song lost Schoolly quite a bit of cash when it was noticed in Abel Ferrara’s (classic) film Bad Lieutenant (used during an extremely graphic and disturbing scene). Abel went on record to say what we were all thinking: that “Signifying Rapper” is “50 million times better than ‘Kashmir’ ever thought of being” and that Zeppelin were no strangers to borrowing a chord or three for most of their songs. Try to find a copy of Bad Lieutenant from before the court case (i.e. with “Signifying Rapper” intact). It’s worth it!
